Rating: 3
A couple of things about the way the recipe is written..... 1, most short ribs including flanken, come already cut into individual ribs. The direction to cut the ribs into 1" pieces would lead one to think that they were specifying boneless ribs since few home kitchens have a butcher's saw. Secondly, braising on the stovetop is tricky for the home kitchen. It's much easier to get a slow, gentle braise in a slow oven. I put it in at about 300 degrees and extend the total cooking time to about 3 hours. This could be why some people didn't have enough sauce at the end; it boiled away. A couple of cook's notes: You need to use a good quality wine here with some heft to it since it makes up the majority of the sauce. Another reason why some people ended up with less sauce, canned tomatoes have already rendered most of their juice. The fresh ones are specified for a reason. For those who said it didn't have much flavor, try it again and this time REALLY brown the meat and REALLY brown those shallots.And don't add any other oil. The meat should have rendered the type of fat you need to get a good fond in the pot without burning. (Olive oil burns faster). Then when you add the wine, boil it a few seconds and scrape up those browned bits into the sauce. That is the key ingredient because the sugar in the shallots will have caramelized into little yummy bits. Then set the ribs in the pot with the cut side of the bones vertical. This lets more good stuff from the bone into the braise while letting the meat soak in the juice.

