Rating: 4
Juliavaile from Charleston, SC on 12/31/07 I've made this recipe several times now, each time a bit differently. After much trial and error, I think I've figured out the KEY to making this utterly outstanding! Here goes: first, season the ribs WELL with salt, fresh pepper, and a little garlic powder. Take your time browning them on all sides-you'll be glad you did later. For the wine reduction, I simmer one bottle of a "big" flavored red like cab, or zin down to about a cup or so. (Merlot is OK, but doesn't create the same "zip"). Depending on the fattiness of the ribs, I may add a little olive oil to the pan for the shallots. For the tomatoes, I substitute diced can tomatoes, and add about 1-2 tsp of sugar to cut the acidity. With the shallots, I add about 8 whole garlic cloves and saute them until carmelized. After everything is put in the pot together, leave them on the stove at a med-low simmer for one hour (try not to open the lid much if you can help it). After the first hour, I throw in the garlic, onion, & diced tomato mixture and simmer on low about 3 hours. The longer you simmer, the more the veggies fall apart and incorporate into the sauce. If the sauce gets too thick, I always keep a little extra wine and beef stock on hand to thin it out a bit. The cook time is the most important factor in creating a very good dish versus one of the most decadent, delicious things you could ever imagine eating. Like one of the other Reviewers mentioned, it's great if you can cook everything a day ahead, so that you can skim the fat before reheating.

